title: For Sale/Trade:  1945 Berlin Luebecker K43 / G43 Gewehr 43 8mm Semi Auto
postcontent:
1945 Berlin Luebecker QVE-1945 Gewehr 43 (K43/G43) All numbers match, no magazine or cleaning rod. It is the original Stock with proof markings (partially covered by paint). Stock was modified to add checkering, fill in sling cut out, and then painted black. Correct phenolic resin hand guard. Serial Number 99**  Marked "99** K.43 qve 45" 

Original bluing of late war (1945) last ditch gun Number matching assembled from parts from subcontractors (please read below). All correct metal: butt plate, bands, trigger guard. The bolt for the 1945 K43 is different than all earlier rifles, it is not ground down. 

Great gun to restore or get replacement stock for.  

Although the nomenclature would lead many to believe that the K43 was a shortened version of the G43, this is not the case. In mid to late 1944, the Germans changed nomenclature on the issue semi-automatic rifle from G43 to K43, supposedly at the request of the Fuhrer. Notable changes at or about this time included omission of the threaded muzzle, a manual type receiver dust cover (to replace the reciprocating type), omission of the milling and "ribbing" on front sight ramps and buttplate trap doors, and hollowed out bolt carrier handles. Gas system components were continuously revised. To say that a K43 would definitely have all of these features is definitely not the case, because there are a myriad of transitional variations between contractors, and at somewhat varying times, and left over or previously rejected parts were used helter-skelter throughout production. A very few 1945 dated rifles produced by Walther are marked G43 or G43/K43. previously rejected or manufactured milled steel recievers made by a subcontractor were already marked G43 and were used here and there in late production.

Berlin Luebecker Machinenfabrik produced the G43 beginning some time in early 1944, when they ceased G41(W) production. BLM used only forged receivers, and had a unique time saving barrel forging machine. Interestingly, throughout production, BLM utilized a part left over from the G41(W): a milled steel bolt housing, instead of a stamped sheetmetal one will sporadically appear. Also unique to BLM were the phenolic resin (also incorrectly called bakelite) Durofol handguards, and the stocks have a rounded and tapered area where the Walther and Gustloff stocks have the flat. Berlin Lubecker changed nomenclature late in 1944 to K43. there are only two letter blocks known of this variety, "i" and "k". this is the second scarcest variety after AC43 guns. Production of DUV44 K43's would amount to less than 20,000 units. Beginning with the "l" letter block in 1945, BLM changed the three letter code from DUV to QVE, and continued production up until the final days of the war, when most finished rifles and parts at this time were shipped to another company owned plant in Czechoslovakia via train. Perhaps this is why the majority of Czech reworked guns have DUV and QVE codes. All in all, approximately 462,000 rifles were completed by all three manufacturers by the end of hostilities.

title: For Sale:  S&W Preformance Center 325 TR Thunder Ranch .45 ACP Revolver
location: Apex, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have a LNIB S&W Mod. 325 TR for sale.  This is a special edition hand built .45 ACP revolver made as a collab with Clint Smith at the Thunder Ranch.  It's an extremely well made gun, hand built by the Performance Center.  Features a 4 inch shrouded barrel with a 1913 under rail for a light attachment, interchangable front sight blades (comes with a brass bead), scandium N frame, 6 shot cylinder with moonclip capability, Performance Center trigger with overtravel stock, all PC internal parts (made of bar stock steel with case bluing rather than standard S&W MIM parts) and all the original kit and kaboodle.  The gun comes in a Eagle Industries soft case with the Thunder Ranch logo on it.  I'll throw in a whole mess of Moonclips and a Wilson Combat De-Mooner.  

  Why you need this gun... This gun is a reloader's dream, it can shoot everything from weak target loads to high pressure +Ps and do it with absolute reliability.  Reloads are super easy, .45ACP's are so short and fat that they're easy to manipulate during reloads, much moreso than other cartridges like .357 when on Moonclips, so you can shoot this gun as fast as a semi-auto.  The trigger combined with a fixed barrel makes it one of the most accurate pistols available, I've fired around 50 rounds thru the gun and it grouped better than my Nighthawk 1911.  Couple all that stuff with the fact that this is a limited edition, hand built collectable S&W, and you're looking at a fantastic investment that's a joy to shoot and own.  

I'm asking 1200$ for the gun, that's what I paid for it, and I'll throw in a box of Remington Golden Sabers.  I'm not looking for long guns, but if you want to offer a trade, I'm looking to standardize my handguns on 9mm and 45ACP Glocks and H&Ks.  I'd take a straight trade for a pair of 9mm Glocks or a straight trade for an H&K 45 Tactical.  I'd also take a trade for a Glock and 700$ cash, or a P30 and 400$ cash.

title: For Sale:  Webley Mark VI Extractor Spring
postcontent: If you have a Webley Mark VI revolver and the extractor doesn't retract following extraction, you may have a weak or broken extractor spring. Since the Mark VI has been out of production for nearly 100 years, replacement parts are hard to come by. If you've searched for this spring, you've found (as I did) that they can't be purchased anywhere at any price. These new-manufacture Webley Mark VI extractor springs are reproductions made of modern spring steel using an original spring as a template. These springs are the same size as the original and fit perfectly in the Mark VI. The parts diagram shows the location of the extractor spring for reference. I don't believe these springs work in any other Webley models, so do your research before you buy. Take advantage of this limited-availability offer to restore your Mark VI to full function before they're all gone. If you buy two or more springs at the same time, I'll ship them together at no additional cost. If you prefer to purchase through ebay, you'll find this spring listed for sale there too.
